ution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Rocco, Angelo, Armando, Donato, Orlando, Antonio, Mario, Carmine, Nunzio, Pasquale, Vittorio, Camillo, Dante, Domenic.  Spanish Carlos, Domingo, Jose, Santos, Alejandro, Ana, Anacleto.","Italian: patronymic or plural form of   Orsino  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Orsino","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Orlando, Annunziata, Salvatore.","Italian: from a diminutive of the vocabulary word or a pet form of the personal name   Orso  ."]}]},{"name":"Gentile","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Angelo, Salvatore, Carmine, Vito, Domenic, Rocco, Giuseppe, Gino, Antonio, Pasquale, Gennaro, Sal.","Italian: from the personal name <i>Gentile</i>, a continuation of Late Latin <i>Gentilis</i>, from Latin <i>gens</i> (genitive <i>gentis</i>) ‘tribe, family, stock’, meaning ‘of the same stock’ and then ‘non-Christian, pagan’; as a medieval name it was an omen or well-wishing name with the sense ‘noble, courteous’, also ‘delicate, charming, graceful’ (Italian <i>gentile</i>). In some cases the surname may have arisen from a nickname, sometimes possibly ironical, from the same word.","English: variant of   Gentle  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Heifetz","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Jewish Eliezer, Gilad, Chayim.","Jewish (from Belarus and Lithuania): nickname from Yiddish <i>kheyfets</i> (Hebrew <i>ḥefets</i>) ‘desire, wish’; or from an archaic personal name of the same etymology.","History: This is one of the old Ashkenazic surnames. In Eastern Europe, it was used by rabbinical families well before the mass adoption of surnames by local Jews at the turn of the 19th century. Most likely, it is the same Ashkenazic family as the one known in northern Italy since the end of the 15th century as <i>Ḥefets</i> in Hebrew sources and <i>Gentile</i> in Christian sources (see   Gentile   3)."]},{"name":"Gentle","meanings":["English (southern): nickname from Middle English, Old French <i>gentil</i> ‘high born, noble’ (from Latin <i>gentilis</i>, from <i>gens</i> ‘family, tribe’, itself from the root <i>gen-</i> ‘to be born’)."]},{"name":"Gentilini","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Aldo, Gino, Bruna, Dante.","Italian: patronymic or plural form of a diminutive of   Gentile  ."]},{"name":"Gentili","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Amilcare, Enrico, Leno, Primo, Romolo, Sylvio, Vincenzo.","Italian: patronymic or plural form of   Gentile  ."]},{"name":"Gentil","meanings":["Altered form of Italian   Gentile  .","French and Portuguese: nickname from Old French and Portuguese <i>gentil</i> (in Old French a derivative of <i>gent</i>; see   Gent  ) ‘high born, noble’, hence ‘noble of character or conduct, courteous’."]}]},{"name":"II","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["1  ♂ ‘Wondrous’ or ‘enlightenment’.","2  ♀ ‘Fine jade’."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Gentile II Orsini was born in 1242, his father, Bertoldo Orsini, was 12 and his mother, Mrs. Filippa Orsini, was 20. He had at least 1 son and 1 daughter with Clarice Ruffo of Catanzaro. He died in 1314, in Rome, Roma, Lazio, Italy, at the age of 72."},"et":{"1242–1314":"1242–1314","1243–Female":"1243–Surnud","1251–1320":"1251–1320","1260–1280":"1260–1280","1250–Female":"1250–Surnud","1275–1326":"1275–1326","–Female":"Surnud","1230–1288":"1230–1288","1223–1273":"1223–1273","from 1314":"1314","1242":"1242","1275":"1275","1286":"1286","1230":"1230","1273":"1273","1251":"1251","1250":"1250","1260":"1260","1280":"1280","aprile 1288":"aprill 1288","1326":"1326","1314":"1314","1223":"1223","1288":"1288","1320":"1320","1243":"1243","about 1273":"umbes 1273","Aft 1280":"pärast 1280","Comune di Napoli, Città Metropolitana di Napoli, Cam